The == operator in Java is used to compare two objects for reference equality. It returns true if the two objects are the same object, i.e., they have the same memory address. On the other hand, the equals() method is used to compare two objects for value equality, i.e., it returns true if the two objects have the same value, regardless of their memory addresses.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:
```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(str1 == str2); // Output: true

String str3 = "Hello";
String str4 = "Hello";
System.out.println(str3 == str4); // Output: true

String str5 = "Hello";
String str6 = "World";
System.out.println(str5 == str6); // Output: false
```

In the first two examples, the == operator returns true because both strings have the same memory address. In the third example, it returns false because the two strings have different memory addresses, even though they have the same value.

